# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-simons
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] Simon was born into a peasant family in Sanem (otherwise Suessem or Sessenheim).
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] He then moved to Paris for further experience.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] His work was part of the painting event in the art competition at the 1924 Summer Olympics.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] He returned to Luxembourg in the late 1920s.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] From 1930 he worked for the *Tageblatt* and from 1934 for the *A-Z Luxemburger Illustrierte*.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] Because of the political stance of his work and his mockery of Hitler he was twice condemned to death by the Nazi government.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] In 1940 when the Germans invaded he was obliged to flee the country and spent the rest of the war working under a false name in France.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] After the end of the war in 1945 he returned to Luxembourg and resumed his work for the *Tageblatt*.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] He also founded a satirical journal, *De Peck-Villchen*, which he directed until his death.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simon] He died in Esch-sur-Alzette and was buried in Sanem, where a street is named after him, as also in Contern.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Born in 1890, Albert Simons descended from a long line of influential Charlestonians.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Thomas Grange Simons, was a physician and who encouraged public health through the advocacy of proper sewers and infrastructure.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Simons' uncle, William Martin Aiken, was an architect who designed many large classical buildings such as "The Old Post Office Pavilion" in Washington, D.C., and in his capacity as architect to the United States Treasury, the Federal Mint in Philadelphia.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Albert Simons enrolled at the College of Charleston for his first year and completed his B.S. and M.S. degrees in architecture at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] After graduation he traveled through Europe and Northern Africa studying architecture, and finished his trip studying at the Atelier Hébrard in Paris.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] During his travels, Simons created hundreds of wonderful travel sketches and watercolors, fulfilling the Beaux-Arts-instilled desire to learn through sketching great examples of architecture.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Upon returning to Charleston in 1915, he became one of the first instructors of architecture at the Clemson School of Architecture.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] During this time, Simons worked briefly as a partner in the firm of Todd, Simons and Todd, until he volunteered to serve in the U.S.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Simons also volunteered to serve in France in World War II.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] In 1920, Simons joined forces with Samuel Lapham VI to create the firm “Simons & Lapham.” Their practice focused primarily on traditional homes, however, they also did industrial, religious, educational, public, transportation projects and building restoration.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Through the Great Depression, the firm remained successful.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Their main commissions came through the federally funded Works Progress Administration work, such as the College of Charleston gymnasium or large plantation projects funded by wealthy northerners.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Throughout the years though, Simons received local and national acclaim for work in the areas of architectural design, preservation, and city planning.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Samuel & Lapham worked actively with the City of Charleston government to protect and restore historic homes and was extensively involved with the Historic American Buildings Survey.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Some of the firm's most famous work included assistance with restoration of the famous “Rainbow Row”, the renovation of the Planter’s Hotel on Church St., into the Dock Street Theatre, and the design of the new Memminger Auditorium.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] In addition to their practice, both partners co-edited books of detailed historical research on the architecture of Charleston including, *The Octagon Library of Early American Architecture*, Vol 1: Charleston, SC (1927) and *Plantations of the Carolina Low Country* (1939).
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] In Simons' years of work in Charleston, he helped create the first historic district in America, the first Board of Architectural Review (BAR), and worked actively as a Fellows of the American Institute of Architects (AIA).
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Simons would also serve on the boards of many of Charleston’s civic and cultural institutions, including the boards of the College of Charleston, the Charleston Museum, the Charleston Library Society, St.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Michael's Episcopal Church, and the Poetry Society of Charleston.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Albert Simons also worked closely with the City to decide the placement and design of the public housing projects in Charleston.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] These low rise (none over two stories) brick apartments were connected in the town house style with generous open space in both the front and the back.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] They were dispersed throughout several neighborhoods on the Charleston peninsula in a way that integrated them into the fabric of the city.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Simons also accumulated a collection of architectural salvage that he donated to the Charleston Museum to present it from feeding the market for salvage and incentivizing owners to gut their historic properties.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] The museum sold the collection at auction around 2009.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Albert Simons began teaching at the College of Charleston in 1924, and created the first Art History course at the College later that year.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] He continued to teach at the college until 1948.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] He helped this single course evolve into the School of the Arts.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] The College named the Albert Simons Center for the Arts for him at the cornerstone-laying ceremony in 1977.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Milner, FAIA (2011), Andres Duany, FAIA, and Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk (2012), Allan Greenberg and Charles, Prince of Wales (2013), Richard Jenrette and Thomas Gordon Smith (2014), Antoinette J.
[src:albert-simons/albert-simons] Awardees are announced during January for the spring ceremony.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He was the originator and leading practitioner of "canonical classicism," one of many design responses to postmodernism emerging in the mid-1970s.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] In 2006, he was the first American to be awarded the Richard H.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Driehaus Prize for Classical Architecture in recognition of his major contributions to architectural design and scholarship.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Greenberg was born on September 7, 1938 in Johannesburg, South Africa.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He was educated at the University of the Witwatersrand, where he studied classical, Gothic, and modern architecture.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He attributes his thorough grounding in architectural history to the rigors of his study there.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Professors required students to memorize and draw the plans of famous buildings at will.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Following a short working career in South Africa, Greenberg moved to London with the intention of studying there, and briefly considered taking a job with Le Corbusier.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] After a short stay in England he left for Denmark to work in the studio of the leading Scandinavian modernist architect Jørn Utzon during the design of the Sydney Opera House.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He subsequently took a job in Helsinki with Viljo Revell, perhaps the best known Finnish architect after Alvar Aalto, whom Greenberg admired greatly.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] In 1963, he moved his Danish wife and young family to America.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He was admitted to the architecture program at Yale, headed by the Brutalist architect Paul Marvin Rudolph.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Like fellow foreign students Norman Foster and Richard Rogers, Greenberg sought a fresh approach to Modernism in a country that was advancing faster than Europe in technology and architectural theory.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] After receiving his Master of Architecture degree from Yale University in 1965, he spent two years in the City of New Haven’s Redevelopment Agency and later served as Architectural Consultant to Connecticut’s Chief Justice from 1967 to 1979.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He taught at Yale under deans Charles W.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Moore and Herman Spiegel, watching the student upheavals of the late 1960s, and helped to develop the school's undergraduate major in architecture.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] It was during the early 1970s that Greenberg became disillusioned with orthodox Modernism, turning instead to postmodernist critiques offered by Yale colleagues Robert Venturi and Denise Scott Brown.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Greenberg's work in the mid-1970s was influenced both by the American "grays" (Moore, Venturi, Robert A.M.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Stern, *et al.*) with whom he became associated, and by modern classicists such as Edwin Lutyens and Mott B.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] But as he came to better understand the achievements of these 20th-century masters, he increasingly pushed his work toward a more traditional vocabulary.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] In 1980, Greenberg contributed a Postmodern architectural facade to The Presence of the Past exhibition at the Venice Biennale, which include facades by many architects engaged in Postmodernism.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] His breakthrough projects came in the early 1980s with his design of a large country house for Peter and Sandra Brant in Greenwich, Connecticut (a commission wrested from Venturi), and George Shultz's extensive classical suite at the State Department in Washington, D.C.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] After their publication Greenberg's office flourished, and many students interested in traditional design came to New Haven to work with him.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] No architect in America has had a more profound influence on the younger generation of traditional architects who are practicing today.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Greenberg has also taught at the University of Pennsylvania, the Division of Historic Preservation at Columbia University, and the University of Notre Dame.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Allan Greenberg, Architect, LLC was established in 1972 and had offices in Alexandria, Virginia and New York City before Greenberg retired in 2021.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] The firm's work covered a broad range of buildings in the United States and overseas.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Projects included master plans, feasibility studies, new construction, renovations, restorations, and interior and furniture design for academic, institutional, religious, commercial, residential, and retail clients.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Greenberg wrote both scholarly and popular books and articles on the dynamic and enduring qualities of traditional architecture and design.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] His extensive body of published work includes the books *George Washington, Architect* (1999), *The Architecture of Democracy: American Architecture and the Legacy of the Revolution* (2006), and *Lutyens and the Modern Movement* (2007).
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] A monograph of his work appeared in 1995.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] More recently, a monograph "Allan Greenberg: Classical Architect" was published by Rizzoli in 2013.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] Greenberg received his U.S. citizenship in 1973.
[src:albert-simons/allan-greenberg] He is married to the painter Judith Seligson, his second wife.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The **American Institute of Architects** (**AIA**) is a professional organization for architects in the United States.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA offers education, government advocacy, community redevelopment, and public outreach programs, and collaborates with other stakeholders in the design and construction industries..
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] While many US-based architects are members of the AIA, it is not a professional requirement.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The American Institute of Architects (AIA) was founded in 1857 in New York City by a group of thirteen architects.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The founding members include Charles Babcock, Henry W.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Cleaveland, Henry Dudley, Leopold Eidlitz, Edward Gardiner, Richard Morris Hunt, Detlef Lienau, Fred A.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Petersen, Jacob Wrey Mould, John Welch, Richard M.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Wells, with Richard Upjohn serving as the first president.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] They held their inaugural meeting on February 23, 1857, and invited 16 additional architects to join, including Alexander Jackson Davis, Thomas U.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Walter, Frederick Clarke Withers, and Calvert Vaux.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] There were no architectural schools or licensing laws in the United States at the time, allowing anyone to claim to be an architect.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] By March 10, 1857, they had drafted a constitution and bylaws under the name New York Society of Architects.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The name was later changed to **The** **American Institute of Architects** at the suggestion of Thomas U.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] On April 15, 1857, the members signed the new constitution, having previously filed a certificate of incorporation two days earlier.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The following year, the constitution was amended to include the mission of promoting the artistic, scientific, and practical aspects of architecture, facilitating professional interaction and camaraderie, raising the profession's standing, and uniting architects for the advancement of the field.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] In the 1860s, architects from other cities began joining AIA.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] By the 1880s, chapters had been established in Albany, Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, Cincinnati, Indianapolis, Philadelphia, Rhode Island, San Francisco, St.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] As of 2008, AIA boasts over 200 chapters.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] In 1898, the AIA moved into its new national headquarters in the historic Octagon House, in Washington, D.C.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA rented the building for 4 years, and then purchased it in 1902.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] In the mid-1960s, a design competition was held to select an architect for a new AIA headquarters to be located at 1735 New York Avenue NW, in Washington, D.C.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Mitchell Giurgola Architects won the competition but failed to gain approval from the United States Commission of Fine Arts for the design concept.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Subsequently, the firm resigned from the commission, and The Architects Collaborative (TAC) was chosen to redesign the building.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Led by TAC principals Norman Fletcher and Howard Elkus, the design was ultimately approved in 1970 and completed in 1973.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA's headquarters also serves as the home of the American Institute of Architecture Students, the Association of Collegiate Schools of Architecture, and the National Architectural Accrediting Board.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The American Institute of Architects (AIA) has a membership of over 100,000 licensed architects and associated professionals.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA members adhere to a code of ethics and professional conduct designed to demonstrate commitment to upholding the highest standards in professional practice and dedication.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA): While they do not hold a license to practice architecture, associate members work under the supervision of an architect in a professional or technical capacity.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] They may have earned professional degrees in architecture, work as faculty members in architecture programs, or be interns earning credit toward licensure.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] **International associate members**: This category is for individuals who hold an architecture license or its equivalent from a licensing authority outside the United States.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] **Emeritus members**: These members have maintained AIA membership for 15 consecutive years and are either at least 70 years old or incapacitated and unable to work in the architecture profession.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] **Allied members**: Allied members are professionals whose work is related to the building and design communities.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] This includes engineers, landscape architects, planners, and senior executive staff from building and design-related companies, such as publishers, product manufacturers, and research firms.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Allied membership represents a partnership between the AIA and the American Architectural Foundation.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA's most esteemed recognition is the Fellow of The American Institute of Architects (FAIA) designation.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] This honor is awarded to members who have made nationally significant contributions to the profession.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Approximately 2% of all members, or slightly more than 2,600 individuals, have been elevated to the AIA College of Fellows.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Prominent foreign architects may also be elected as Honorary Fellows of AIA, gaining recognition within the college.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA operates under the governance of a board of directors and maintains a staff of nearly 200 employees.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] While AIA serves as a national organization, its reach is extended through its 217 local and state chapters.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Chapters span the United States and its territories.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA components also operate in several international locations, including the United Kingdom, Continental Europe, the Middle East, Japan, Hong Kong, Shanghai, and Canada.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] These chapters offer programming and direct services to support AIA members at various stages of their professional careers.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] In June 2013, The American Institute of Architects unveiled the "Designing Recovery" initiative during CGI America, an annual event of the Clinton Global Initiative.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] This initiative involved a design contest conducted in partnership with charitable organizations such as Make It Right, SBP, and Architecture for Humanity.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The contest focused on single-family housing designs aimed at enhancing the quality, diversity, and resilience of housing in each community.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The portfolio of designs, including those from non-winning entries, was made available to communities recovering from natural disasters.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Dow Building Solutions sponsored the contest, providing a total prize money of $30,000.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] The prize was equally distributed among three winning designs from New Orleans, Louisiana; Joplin, Missouri; and New York City.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA members actively contribute to their profession and communities by participating in various professional interest areas, ranging from design to regional and urban development.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] They also engage with professional academies that foster the generation of new ideas and responses.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Local components provide support to younger professionals through programs such as the Intern Development Program, Architect Registration Exam preparation courses, and employment referral services.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA organizes the AIA Conference on Architecture & Design, held annually in late spring or early summer, which attracts the largest gathering of architects worldwide.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA attempts to meet the needs and interests of the nation's architects and the public by raising public awareness of the value of architecture and the importance of good design.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] To mark AIA's 150th anniversary and to showcase how members have helped shape the built environment, AIA and Harris Interactive released findings from a public poll that asked Americans to name their favorite 150 works of architecture, America's Favorite Architecture.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] AIA recognizes individuals and organizations for outstanding achievements in support of the architecture profession and AIA.
[src:albert-simons/american-institute-of-architects] Awards include the Next LA Merit Award, the Next Design Award, and the Next Design Honor Award.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Duany was born in New York City but grew up in Cuba until 1960.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] He attended The Choate School and Aiglon College and received his undergraduate degree in architecture and urban planning from Princeton University (1971).
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] After a year of study at the École des Beaux-Arts in Paris, he received a master's degree from the Yale School of Architecture (1974).
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] He has also received an honorary Doctorate of Fine Arts from Yale School of Architecture (2023).
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] In 1977, Duany co-founded the Miami firm Arquitectonica with his wife, Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk, Bernardo Fort-Brescia, Laurinda Spear, and Hervin Romney.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Arquitectonica was known for its playful, Latin-American influenced modernism.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] The firm's Atlantis Condominium was featured in the opening credits of the television series *Miami Vice*.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] In 1980, Duany and Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk founded Duany Plater-Zyberk & Company (DPZ), an architecture firm based in Miami.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] DPZ participated in the formation of the international urban planning movement known as New Urbanism, intended to offer an alternative to suburban sprawl and urban disinvestment.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] The firm first received recognition as the designer of new towns such as Seaside, Florida and Kentlands, Maryland.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] The firm has since completed designs and codes for over three hundred new towns, regional plans, and inner-city revitalization projects.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Duany is also considered to be a representative of New Classical Architecture.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Duany is a co-founder and emeritus board member of the Congress for the New Urbanism (CNU), established in 1993.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] He has co-authored five books: *Suburban Nation: The Rise of Sprawl and the Decline of the American Dream*; *The New Civic Art*; *The Smart Growth Manual*; *Garden Cities*; and *Landscape Urbanism and Its Discontents*.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Duany has worked as visiting professor at many institutions and holds two honorary doctorates.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] He is a fellow of the American Institute of Architects and an adjunct professor at the University of Miami.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Duany and his partner, Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk, have been awarded several honorary doctorates and awards including the Vincent Scully Prize by the National Building Museum in recognition of their contributions to the American built environment.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Duany has been awarded the Brandeis Award for Architecture, the Thomas Jefferson Medal in Architecture, the Arthur Ross Award in Community Planning, the Richard H.
[src:albert-simons/andres-duany] Driehaus Prize for Classical Architecture, the Society of American Registered Architects International Award, and the Albert Simons Medal of Excellence, among other awards.
[src:albert-simons/architect] An **architect** is a person who plans, designs, and oversees the construction of buildings.
[src:albert-simons/architect] To practice architecture means to provide services in connection with the design of buildings and the space within the site surrounding the buildings that have human occupancy or use as their principal purpose.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Etymologically, the term architect derives from the Latin *architectus*, which derives from the Greek (**arkhi*-*, chief + *tekton*, builder), i.e., chief builder.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The professional requirements for architects vary from location to location.
[src:albert-simons/architect] An architect's decisions affect public safety, and thus the architect must undergo specialised training consisting of advanced education and a *practicum* (or internship) for practical experience to earn a license to practice architecture.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Practical, technical, and academic requirements for becoming an architect vary by jurisdiction though the formal study of architecture in academic institutions has played a pivotal role in the development of the profession.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Throughout ancient and medieval history, most architectural design and construction was carried out by artisans—such as stone masons and carpenters—who rose to the role of master builders.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Until modern times, there was no clear distinction between architect and engineer.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In Europe, the titles *architect* and *engineer* were primarily geographical variations that referred to the same person, often used interchangeably.
[src:albert-simons/architect] "Architect" derives from Greek ἀρχιτέκτων (*arkhitéktōn*, "master builder," "chief *tektōn*").
[src:albert-simons/architect] It is suggested that various developments in technology and mathematics allowed the development of the professional 'gentleman' architect, separate from the hands-on craftsman.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Paper was not used in Europe for drawing until the 15th century but became increasingly available after 1500.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The availability of both paper and pencils allowed pre-construction drawings to be made by professionals.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Concurrently, the introduction of linear perspective and innovations such as the use of different projections to describe a three-dimensional building in two dimensions, together with an increased understanding of dimensional accuracy, helped building designers communicate their ideas.
[src:albert-simons/architect] However, development was gradual and slow-going.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Until the 18th century, buildings continued to be designed and set out by craftsmen, with the exception of high-status projects.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In most developed countries only those qualified with an appropriate license, certification, or registration with a relevant body (often a government) may legally practice architecture.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Such licensure usually requires a university degree, successful completion of exams, and a training period.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Representation of oneself as an architect through the use of terms and titles were restricted to licensed individuals by law, although in general, derivatives such as architectural designer were not legally protected.
[src:albert-simons/architect] To practice architecture implies the ability to practice independently of supervision.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In many places, independent, non-licensed individuals may perform design services outside of professional restrictions, such as the design of houses or other smaller structures.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In the architectural profession, technical and environmental knowledge, design, and construction management require an understanding of business as well as design.
[src:albert-simons/architect] However, design is the driving force throughout the project and beyond.
[src:albert-simons/architect] An architect accepts a commission from a client.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The commission might involve preparing feasibility reports, building audits, and designing a building or several buildings, structures, and the spaces among them.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect participates in developing the requirements the client wants in the building.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Throughout the project (planning to occupancy), the architect coordinates a design team.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Structural, mechanical, and electrical engineers are hired by the client or architect, who must ensure that the work is coordinated to construct the design.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect, once hired by a client, is responsible for creating a design concept that meets the requirements of that client and provides a facility suitable for the required use.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect must meet with and ask questions to the client, to ascertain all the requirements (and nuances) of the planned project.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Often, the full brief is not clear in the beginning.
[src:albert-simons/architect] It involves a degree of risk in the design undertaking.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect may make early proposals to the client, which may rework the terms of the brief.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The "program" (or brief) is essential to producing a project that meets all the needs of the owner.
[src:albert-simons/architect] This becomes a guide for the architect in creating the design concept.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Design proposals are generally expected to be both imaginative and pragmatic.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Much depends upon the time, place, finance, culture, and available crafts and technology in which the design takes place.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The extent and nature of these expectations will vary.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Foresight is a prerequisite when designing buildings, as it is a very complex and demanding undertaking.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The selection of appropriate materials and technology must be considered, tested, and reviewed at an early stage in the design to ensure there are no setbacks (such as higher-than-expected costs) that could occur later in the project.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The site and its surrounding environment, as well as the culture and history of the place, will also influence the design.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The design must also balance increasing concerns with environmental sustainability.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect may introduce (intentionally or not), aspects of mathematics and architecture, new or current architectural theory, or references to architectural history.
[src:albert-simons/architect] A key part of the design is that the architect often must consult with engineers, surveyors, and other specialists throughout the design, ensuring that aspects such as structural supports and air conditioning elements are coordinated.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The control and planning of construction costs are also part of these consultations.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Coordination of the different aspects involves a high degree of specialized communication, including advanced computer technology such as building information modeling (BIM), computer-aided design (CAD), and cloud-based technologies.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Finally, at all times, the architect must report back to the client, who may have reservations or recommendations that might introduce further variables into the design.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Architects also deal with local and federal jurisdictions regarding regulations and building codess.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect might need to comply with local planning and zoning laws such as required setbacks, height limitations, parking requirements, transparency requirements (windows), and land use.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Some jurisdictions require adherence to design and historic preservation guidelines.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Health and safety risks form a vital part of the current design, and in some jurisdictions, design reports and records are required to include ongoing considerations of materials and contaminants, waste management and recycling, traffic control, and fire safety.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Previously, architects employed drawings to illustrate and generate design proposals.
[src:albert-simons/architect] While conceptual sketches are still widely used by architects, computer technology has now become the industry standard.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Furthermore, design may include the use of photos, collages, prints, linocuts, 3D scanning technology, and other media in design production.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Increasingly, computer software is shaping how architects work.
[src:albert-simons/architect] BIM technology allows for the creation of a virtual building that serves as an information database for the sharing of design and building information throughout the life cycle of the building's design, construction, and maintenance.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Virtual reality (VR) presentations are becoming more common for visualizing structural designs and interior spaces from the point-of-view perspective.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Since modern buildings are known to release carbon into the atmosphere, increasing controls are being placed on buildings and associated technology to reduce emissions, increase energy efficiency, and make use of renewable energy sources.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Renewable energy sources may be designed into the proposed building by local or national renewable energy providers.
[src:albert-simons/architect] As a result, the architect is required to remain abreast of current regulations that are continually being updated.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Some new developments exhibit extremely low energy use or passive solar building design.
[src:albert-simons/architect] However, the architect is also increasingly being required to provide initiatives in a wider environmental sense.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Examples of this include making provisions for low-energy transport, natural daylighting instead of artificial lighting, natural ventilation instead of air conditioning, pollution, and waste management, use of recycled materials, and employment of materials which can be easily recycled.
[src:albert-simons/architect] As the design becomes more advanced and detailed, specifications and detail designs are made of all the elements and components of the building.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Techniques in the production of a building are continually advancing which places a demand on the architect to ensure that he or she remains up to date with these advances.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Architects typically put projects to tender on behalf of their clients, advise them on the award of the project to a general contractor, facilitate and administer a contract of agreement, which is often between the client and the contractor.
[src:albert-simons/architect] This contract is legally binding and covers a wide range of aspects, including the insurance and commitments of all stakeholders, the status of the design documents, provisions for the architect's access, and procedures for the control of the works as they proceed.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Depending on the type of contract used, provisions for further sub-contract tenders may be required.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect may require that some elements be covered by a warranty which specifies the expected life and other aspects of the material, product, or work.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In most jurisdictions prior notification to the relevant authority must be given before commencement of the project, giving the local authority notice to carry out independent inspections.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The architect will then review and inspect the progress of the work in coordination with the local authority.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In the United Kingdom and other countries, a quantity surveyor is often part of the team to provide cost consulting.
[src:albert-simons/architect] With large, complex projects, an independent construction manager is sometimes hired to assist in the design and management of the construction.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In many jurisdictions mandatory certification or assurance of the completed work or part of the work is required.
[src:albert-simons/architect] This demand for certification entails a high degree of risk; therefore, regular inspections of the work as it progresses on site is required to ensure that the design is in compliance itself as well as following all relevant statutes and permissions.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Recent decades have seen the rise of specialisations within the profession.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Many architects and architectural firms focus on certain project types (e.g. healthcare, retail, public housing, and event management), technological expertise, or project delivery methods.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Some architects specialise in building code, building envelope, sustainable design, technical writing, historic preservation (US) or conservation (UK), and accessibility.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Many architects elect to move into real-estate (property) development, corporate facilities planning, project management, construction management, chief sustainability officers interior design, city planning, user experience design, and design research.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Although there are variations in each location, most of the world's architects are required to register with the appropriate jurisdiction.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Architects are typically required to meet three common requirements: education, experience, and examination.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Basic educational requirements generally consist of a university degree in architecture.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The experience requirement for degree candidates is usually satisfied by a practicum or internship (most often two to three years).
[src:albert-simons/architect] Finally, a Registration Examination or a series of exams is required prior to licensure.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Professionals who engaged in the design and supervision of construction projects before the late 19th century were not necessarily trained in a separate architecture program in an academic setting.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Instead, they often trained under established architects.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Prior to modern times, there was no distinction between architects and engineers and the title used varied depending on geographical location.
[src:albert-simons/architect] They often carried the title of master builder or surveyor after serving a number of years as an apprentice (such as Sir Christopher Wren).
[src:albert-simons/architect] The formal study of architecture in academic institutions played a pivotal role in the development of the profession as a whole, serving as a focal point for advances in architectural technology and theory.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The use of "Architect" or abbreviations such as "Ar." as a title attached to a person's name was regulated by law in some countries.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Architects' fee structure is typically based on a percentage of construction value, as a rate per unit area of the proposed construction, hourly rates, or a fixed lump sum fee.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Combination of these structures is also common.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Fixed fees are usually based on a project's allocated construction cost and could range between 4 and 12% of new construction cost for commercial and institutional projects, depending on the project's size and complexity.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Residential projects range from 12 to 20%.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Renovation projects typically command higher percentages such as 15–20%.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Overall billings for architectural firms range widely, depending on their location and economic climate.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Billings have traditionally been dependent on local economic conditions, but with rapid globalization, this is becoming less of a factor for large international firms.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Salaries could also vary depending on experience, position within the firm (i.e. staff architect, partner, or shareholder, etc.), and the size and location of the firm.
[src:albert-simons/architect] A number of national professional organizations exist to promote career and business development in architecture.
[src:albert-simons/architect] A wide variety of prizes is awarded by national professional associations and other bodies, recognizing accomplished architects, their buildings, structures, and professional careers.
[src:albert-simons/architect] The most lucrative award an architect can receive is the Pritzker Prize, sometimes termed the "Nobel Prize for architecture".
[src:albert-simons/architect] The inaugural Pritzker Prize winner was Philip Johnson who was cited as having "50 years of imagination and vitality embodied in a myriad of museums, theatres libraries, houses gardens and corporate structures".
[src:albert-simons/architect] The Pritzker Prize has been awarded for forty-two straight editions without interruption, and there are now 22 countries with at least one winning architect.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Other prestigious architectural awards are the Royal Gold Medal, the AIA Gold Medal (US), AIA Gold Medal (Australia), and the Praemium Imperiale.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Those elected to chartered membership of the RIBA after 1971 may use the initials RIBA but cannot use the old ARIBA and FRIBA.
[src:albert-simons/architect] An honorary fellow may use the initials Hon.
[src:albert-simons/architect] FRIBA, and an international fellow may use the initials Int.
[src:albert-simons/architect] Architects in the US who have made contributions to the profession through design excellence or architectural education or have in some other way advanced the profession are elected Fellows of the American Institute of Architects and can write FAIA after their name.
[src:albert-simons/architect] In Hong Kong, those elected to chartered membership may use the initial HKIA, and those who have made a special contribution after nomination and election by the Hong Kong Institute of Architects (HKIA), may be elected as fellow members of HKIA and may use FHKIA after their name.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The study of art’s history emerged as a way to document and interpret artistic production.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Early traditions of art-historical writing developed in several cultures, including Ancient Greece, Imperial China, and Renaissance Italy, each producing influential figures and approaches that shaped later scholarship.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] As an academic discipline, art history emerged in the 19th century and was a largely Eurocentric field, concentrating on Western definitions of the fine and decorative arts, particularly painting, drawing, sculpture, and architecture.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In the contemporary era, however, art history has expanded to examine broader aspects of visual culture, including the various cultural, political, and socioeconomic issues related to art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Today, art history is a broad academic field encompassing numerous methodologies and interdisciplinary approaches to the study of artistic production globally, including European, Asian, African, or American Indigenous arts, among others.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Some of the subfields include Marxist art history, feminist art history, iconography and the study of symbols, visual culture studies, and design history.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Art historians employ a number of methods in their research so they can examine work in the context of its time.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] This is professionally done in a manner which respects its creator's motivations and imperatives; with consideration of the desires and prejudices of its patrons and sponsors.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] A comparative analysis of themes and approaches of the creator's colleagues and teachers along with consideration of iconography and symbolism is part of the examination.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] This approach examines the work of art in the context of the world within which it was created.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Art historians also often examine work through an analysis of form; that is, the creator's use of line, shape, color, texture and composition.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] This approach examines how the artist uses a two-dimensional picture plane or the three dimensions of sculptural or architectural space to create their art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The way these individual elements are employed results in representational or non-representational art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] An analysis of iconography is a large branch of art history which focuses on particular design elements of an object.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Through a close reading of such elements, it is possible to trace their lineage, and with it draw conclusions regarding the origins and trajectory of these motifs.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In turn, it is possible to make any number of observations regarding the social, cultural, economic and aesthetic values of those responsible for producing the object.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Art historians may also work alongside or as art conservators, helping restore and conserve artworks.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Conservation is a scientific field that is crucial to historians work, due to them needing to observe a work that is a condition good enough to be examined.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Training in art conservation typically involves coursework in chemistry as well as the practice and history of art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Most art historians choose a specific historical period within art history to specialize or gain an academic degree in.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Concentrations on art movements, periods and certain fields such as Prehistoric art, Ancient art, Medieval art, Renaissance art, Romanticism, Realism, Modern art, Contemporary art, Pop art, Feminist art, Queer art and much more are common in the academic world.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] These periods of art movements attempt to cover the broader aspect of art history while distinctively separating them.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In the 1970s, Linda Nochlin's essay "Why Have There Been No Great Women Artists?" helped to ignite feminist art history and remains one of the most widely read essays about female artists.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] This was followed by a 1972 College Art Association Panel, chaired by Nochlin, entitled "Eroticism and the Image of Woman in Nineteenth-Century Art".
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Within a decade, scores of papers, articles, and essays sustained a growing momentum, fueled by the Second-wave feminist movement, of critical discourse surrounding women's interactions with the arts as both artists and subjects.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The few who did succeed were treated as anomalies and did not provide a model for subsequent success.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Griselda Pollock is another prominent feminist art historian, whose use of psychoanalytic theory is described above.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] While feminist art history can focus on any time period and location, much attention has been given to the Modern era.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Some of this scholarship centers on the feminist art movement, which referred specifically to the experience of women.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Often, feminist art history offers a critical "re-reading" of the Western art canon, such as Carol Duncan's re-interpretation of *Les Demoiselles d'Avignon*.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Two pioneers of the field are Mary Garrard and Norma Broude.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Their anthologies *Feminism and Art History: Questioning the Litany*, *The Expanding Discourse: Feminism and Art History*, and *Reclaiming Feminist Agency: Feminist Art History After Postmodernism* are substantial efforts to bring feminist perspectives into the discourse of art history.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The pair also co-founded the Feminist Art History Conference.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Art historians are often employed by museums due to their expertise in the field.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Galleries, and archives are places where art historians may be in charge of exhibits, research or collections, depending on specialization factors.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Museum studies, including the history of museum collecting and display, is now a specialized field of study, as is the history of collecting.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The earliest surviving writing on art that can be classified as art history are the passages in Pliny the Elder's *Natural History* (c.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] AD 77–79), concerning the development of Greek sculpture and painting.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] From them it is possible to trace the ideas of Xenokrates of Sicyon (c.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] 280 BC), a Greek sculptor who was perhaps the first art historian.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Pliny's work, while mainly an encyclopaedia of the sciences, has thus been influential from the Renaissance onwards.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] (Passages about techniques used by the painter Apelles c.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] (332–329 BC), have been especially well-known.) Similar, though independent, developments occurred in the 6th century China, where a canon of worthy artists was established by writers in the scholar-official class.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] These writers, being necessarily proficient in calligraphy, were artists themselves.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The artists are described in the *Six Principles of Painting* formulated by Xie He.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Giorgio Vasari, a Tuscan painter, sculptor and author of the *Lives of the Most Excellent Painters, Sculptors, and Architects*, has been credited with writing the first true *history* of art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] He emphasized art's progression and development, which was a milestone in this field.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] His work was a personal and a historical account, featuring biographies of individual Italian artists, many of whom were his contemporaries and personal acquaintances.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The most renowned of these was Michelangelo.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Vasari's writings about art were enormously influential, and served as a model for many.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Scholars such as Johann Joachim Winckelmann (1717–1768) criticized Vasari's "cult" of artistic personality, and argued that the real emphasis in the study of art should be the views of the learned beholder and not the viewpoint of the artist.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Winckelmann's writings thus were the beginnings of art criticism.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Winckelmann critiqued the artistic excesses of Baroque and Rococo forms, and was instrumental in reforming taste in favor of Neoclassicism.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Winckelmann's work marked the entry of art history into the high-philosophical discourse of German culture.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Winckelmann was read avidly by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Friedrich Schiller, both of whom began to write on the history of art, and his account of the Laocoön group occasioned a response by Lessing.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The emergence of art as a major subject of philosophical speculation was solidified by the appearance of Immanuel Kant's *Critique of Judgment* in 1790, and was furthered by Hegel's *Lectures on Aesthetics*.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Hegel's philosophy served as the direct inspiration for Karl Schnaase's work.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Schnaase's survey was published contemporaneously with a similar work by Franz Theodor Kugler.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Heinrich Wölfflin (1864–1945), who studied under Burckhardt in Basel, is considered to be one of the most influential scholars of modern art history.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] He introduced a scientific approach to the history of art, focusing on three concepts.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Firstly, he attempted to study art using psychology, particularly by applying the work of Wilhelm Wundt.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] He argued, among other things, that art and architecture are good if they resemble the human body.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] For example, houses were good if their façades looked like faces.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Secondly, he introduced the idea of studying art through comparison.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] By comparing individual paintings to each other, he was able to make distinctions of style.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] His book *Renaissance and Baroque* developed this idea, and was the first to show how these stylistic periods differed from one another.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In contrast to Giorgio Vasari, Wölfflin was uninterested in the biographies of artists.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] He proposed the creation of an "art history without names." He also studied art based on ideas of nationhood.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] He was particularly interested in whether there was an inherently "Italian" and an inherently "German" style.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] This last interest was most fully articulated in his monograph on the German artist Albrecht Dürer.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In the late 19th century, a major school of art-historical thought developed at the University of Vienna.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The first generation of the Vienna School was dominated by Alois Riegl and Franz Wickhoff, both students of Moritz Thausing, and was characterized by a tendency to reassess neglected or disparaged periods in the history of art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Riegl and Wickhoff both wrote extensively on the art of late antiquity, which before them had been considered as a period of decline from the classical ideal.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Riegl also contributed to the revaluation of the Baroque.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The next generation of professors at Vienna included Max Dvořák, Julius von Schlosser, Hans Tietze, Karl Maria Swoboda, and Josef Strzygowski.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] A number of the most important twentieth-century art historians, including Ernst Gombrich, received their degrees at Vienna at this time.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The term "Second Vienna School" (or "New Vienna School") usually refers to the following generation of Viennese scholars, including Hans Sedlmayr, Otto Pächt, and Guido Kaschnitz von Weinberg.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] These scholars began in the 1930s to return to the work of the first generation, particularly to Riegl and his concept of *Kunstwollen*, and attempted to develop it into a full-blown art-historical methodology.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Sedlmayr, in particular, rejected the minute study of iconography, patronage, and other approaches grounded in historical context, preferring instead to concentrate on the aesthetic qualities of a work of art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] As a result, the Second Vienna School gained a reputation for unrestrained and irresponsible formalism.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] This latter tendency was, however, by no means shared by all members of the school; Pächt, for example, was himself Jewish, and was forced to leave Vienna in the 1930s.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In 1920, a group of scholars gathered in Hamburg to study Iconography.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The most prominent among them were Erwin Panofsky, Aby Warburg, Fritz Saxl and Gertrud Bing.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Together they developed much of the vocabulary that continues to be used in the 21st century by art historians.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] "Iconography"—with roots meaning "symbols from writing" refers to subject matter of art derived from written sources—especially scripture and mythology.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] "Iconology" is a broader term that referred to all symbolism, whether derived from a specific text or not.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Today art historians sometimes use these terms interchangeably.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Panofsky, in his early work, also developed the theories of Riegl, but became eventually more preoccupied with iconography, and in particular with the transmission of themes related to classical antiquity in the Middle Ages and Renaissance.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In this respect his interests coincided with those of Warburg, the son of a wealthy family who had assembled a library in Hamburg, devoted to the study of the classical tradition in later art and culture.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Under Saxl's auspices, this library was developed into a research institute, affiliated with the University of Hamburg, where Panofsky taught.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Warburg died in 1929, and in the 1930s Saxl and Panofsky, both Jewish, were forced to leave Hamburg.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Saxl settled in London, bringing Warburg's library with him and establishing the Warburg Institute.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Panofsky settled in Princeton at the Institute for Advanced Study.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In this respect they were part of an extraordinary influx of German art historians into the English-speaking academy in the 1930s.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] These scholars were largely responsible for establishing art history as a legitimate field of study in the English-speaking world, and the influence of Panofsky's methodology, in particular, determined the course of American art history for a generation.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] By the Mid-20th Century, the ideas of Marxism began to spread rapidly throughout Europe along with a further inquiry of the history of art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] The Frankfurt School, using critical theory, were influential figures in the advancement of studying art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Along with Marxists before the 1920s, such as Georgi Plekhanov and Friedrich Engels, using historical materialism, to analyze the development of the arts within society.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Within the Frankfurt School, philosopher Walter Benjamin, wrote his 1935 essay "The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction", in which Benjamin argued that an "aura" is found within artworks: its original presence in time and space.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] He suggests a work of art's aura is in a state of decay because it is becoming more and more difficult to apprehend the time and space in which a piece of art is created.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Benjamin's theory closely relates to Affect theory.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Class society has also been a foundation for studying the development of the arts.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In the early 20th Century and late 19th, historical materialism was an active theory of history that was beginning to gain traction, and still to this day is used worldwide by art historians.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Georgi Plekhanov is considered to be a pioneer in progressing the use of materialist thinking within the study of art.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] His work "Historical Materialism and the Arts" written in 1899, describes how historical materialism can be used against an idealist conclusion of art to reach a clearer outlook on the topic.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Marxists, like Plekhanov, argue that while artistic periods and revolutions obey their own logic, ultimately art is confined within the limits of the mode of production.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Importantly, Marxists believe that the ideas in society, including art, are an expression of one or another of the contending classes existing in that mode of production.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In the United States, one of the most important art history organization is the College Art Association.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] It organizes an annual conference and publishes the *Art Bulletin* and *Art Journal*.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] Similar organizations exist in other parts of the world, as well as for specializations, such as architectural history and Renaissance art history.
[src:albert-simons/art-history] In the UK, for example, the Association of Art Historians is the premiere organization, and it publishes a journal titled *Art History*.
